  "prompt": "How can I record video with Drift Ghost-S while charging?",
  "response": "You can record video with the Drift Ghost-S while charging, but there are a couple of things you need to consider:\n\n**1. Power Source and Compatibility:**\n\n*   **USB Power Adapter:** The most common way is to use a USB power adapter plugged into a wall outlet or a power bank.  Make sure the adapter provides sufficient power output.  The Drift Ghost-S typically requires a standard USB 5V/1A (5 volts, 1 amp) charger.  Using a higher amperage charger *should* be fine, as the camera will only draw what it needs, but avoid anything with a drastically lower amperage (e.g., 0.5A) as it might not provide enough power to record and charge simultaneously.\n\n*   **USB Port on a Computer:** Connecting the camera to a USB port on a computer *may* work, but often computer USB ports don't provide enough power to both charge and record for extended periods.  The camera might indicate it's charging, but the battery could still drain slowly while recording.\n\n*   **Car Charger:**  A car USB charger is a good option for recording while driving.  Ensure it meets the 5V/1A specification.\n\n**2. Battery Considerations:**\n\n*   **Heat:** Charging generates heat, and recording generates heat. Combining the two can lead to the camera overheating, which can potentially shorten the lifespan of the battery and other components.  Be aware of this, especially if you're recording in a hot environment.\n\n*   **Battery Health:** Long-term, constant charging while recording can potentially degrade the battery's capacity over time. It's generally a good practice to occasionally let the battery discharge somewhat and then recharge it fully.\n\n**3. Recording Time Limitations:**\n\n*   **MicroSD Card Capacity:** The recording time will be limited by the capacity of your microSD card.  Make sure you have a card with sufficient storage for your needs.  Check the Drift Ghost-S manual for the maximum supported card size and recommended speed (class).\n\n*   **File Splitting:** The Ghost-S may split recordings into segments (e.g., 10-minute files) depending on your settings. This is to prevent data loss in case of a power interruption and can also make it easier to manage larger files.\n\n**4. How to Set Up:**\n\n1.  **Connect the Ghost-S to a power source:** Plug the USB cable into the camera and the power adapter/power bank/computer USB port.\n2.  **Turn on the camera:** Press the power button.\n3.  **Verify Charging:** Check the camera's screen or indicator lights to confirm that it's charging. You should see the charging icon.\n4.  **Start Recording:** Press the record button. The camera should begin recording video while continuing to charge.\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **Test Thoroughly:** Before any important recording session, test the setup thoroughly. Make sure the camera is actually charging *while* it's recording. Record a short video and then check the battery level afterwards.\n*   **Check for Overheating:**  Periodically check the camera's temperature, especially during long recording sessions. If it feels excessively hot, stop recording and let it cool down.\n*   **Use a Quality Charger:** A good quality USB power adapter is important for consistent charging and preventing power fluctuations that could damage the camera.\n*   **Consult the Manual:** Always refer to the Drift Ghost-S user manual for the most up-to-date information and recommendations regarding charging and operation.  There might be specific settings or behaviors related to charging while recording that are detailed in the manual.\n*   **Consider External Power Solutions:** For very long recording times, especially in demanding conditions, explore external power solutions designed for action cameras. These can provide more reliable and consistent power.\n",
